Providing you some of the *Frequently Asked Questions* for this question.
I arranged the questions from less to more (frequency).
If you don't know about the solution please have a look at it before reading FAQs. I have attached it below!

**Why hashmap?**
Because we need to store count of trees which can be made with corresponding values of array.

**Why count is initially mapped as 1?**
Since single element can make a tree!

**Why sorted? (Most Frequently Asked Question)**
Inorder to understand this answer, we need to look at another question (Follow up)

**`Why it is A[i] % rootEle == 0 && rootWithCount.find(A[i] / rootEle) != rootWithCount.end() ?`**
**`Why  A[i] % rootEle == 0 ? `**
 We have to check whether any rootEle (previously stored value in hashmap) is a factor of A[i]. 
 As per the question, For a element to be valid root, we should have two childrens whose product is equal to root.

*If we need to get element by multipling any two numbers, atleast one of it has to be its factor.*
 **Example: Root -> 10; Childrens -> 5, 2 Both 5 and 2 are factors.**

**` Why rootWithCount.find(A[i] / rootEle) != rootWithCount.end() ?`**
 We found rootEle as a factor, is there are any element in the map, so that they multiplies to give the root value.

 Now coming back to our question (why sorted)

 **For every number, their factors will be less than it**. SIMPLE SO SORTED.


