solutions.content:
Start to calculate from the smallest element to the biggest element in ```int[] A```.
If there are two elements ```A[s]```, ```A[e]``` where ```A[s]*A[e] == A[i] and s<i && e<i```
that means we have found ```dp[s]*dp[e]``` more trees for element ```A[i]```.
```
class Solution {
    public int numFactoredBinaryTrees(int[] A) {
        long res = 0L, mod = (long) 1000000007;
        long[] dp = new long[A.length];
        Arrays.fill(dp,1);
        Arrays.sort(A);
        for(int i = 1; i < A.length; i++) {
            int s = 0, e = i-1;
            while(s <= e) {
                if(A[s]*A[e] > A[i])e--;
                else if(A[s]*A[e] < A[i])s++;
                else {
                    dp[i] = ((dp[s]*dp[e]*(A[s] == A[e]? 1:2)%mod+dp[i]))%mod;
                    s++;
                }
            }
        }
        for(long d: dp) {
            res = (d+res)%mod;
        }
        return (int)res;
    }
}
```

