solutions.content:
It's extremely slow, but I'm quite proud of what I came up with.
The intuition goes like this: 
Say we're given an array such as [20, 10, 5, 4, 2] (doesn't have to be sorted)
We can choose to break up 20 with 10, 5, 4, or 2 and count trees(20) i.e. the number of trees 20 can form. Start with 10 as the left node of 20 and 20/10 = 2 (which we check if it is in the array). Then we break the problem down into a sub problem where we repeat the same with trees(10) and trees(2).
Once we're done finding trees(10) can form with trees(2), we multiply them together. This is because
trees(2) = length of [[2]] and trees(10) = [[10, 2, 5], [10]] and we can make 20 by using their different combinations.
Since we're going to run into 10 later in the list, we use dynamic programming to memoize trees(10), storing it in a map.
The listed solution stores the index instead which is smarter to do since it's faster to access and under 1e9. We mod by 1e9+7 along the way to make sure it's under overflow.
```
class Solution {
public:
    int mod = 1e9+7;
    unordered_map<int, long> dp;
    unordered_map<int, int> exists;
    long total = 0;
    int numFactoredBinaryTrees(vector<int>& A) {
        for (int i = 0; i < A.size(); i++) {
            exists.insert({A[i], i});
            dp.insert({A[i], 0});
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < A.size(); i++) {
            total = (total + trees(A, i))%mod;
        }
        return total%mod;
    }

    long trees(vector<int>& A, int i) {
        auto searchdp = dp.find(A[i]);
        if (searchdp->second) return searchdp->second;
        searchdp->second = 1;
        for (int j = 0; j < A.size(); j++) {
            auto search = exists.find(A[i]/A[j]);
            if (!(A[i]%A[j]) && search != exists.end()) {
                searchdp->second = (searchdp->second + trees(A, j)*trees(A, search->second)) % mod;
            }
        }
        return searchdp->second;
    }
};
