solutions.content:
The first obvious hint at looking at his problem is that there is no TreeNode definition , so we don't have to actually build a Tree.  Here are the observations that we should get on reading the problem

	1.A tree **CAN NOT** have 1 child.
	2.No of trees possible for a Node with no children = 1
	3.No of trees possible for a Node(a) with valid children(b,c) such that(a=b*c) = no of trees(b)*no(of trees c ). 

3 gives the first condition for DP.i.e we can break into subproblems. Now we need to see if calculating in naive way , we repeat subproblems.Lets take eg of 40-

	1. The factors are {2,20},{20,2},{4,10},{10,4},{5,8},{8,5}.
	2. Now for trees{20,2} = trees(20)*trees(2);
	3. notice that trees(20) is gonna calculate the subproblem trees(10) and so is the pair {4,10}. Thus we have the second condition for DP, repetition of sub problems.

Now we need to populate 2 things for our algorithm.
	1. A hashmap for each element in the arr with a list of all pairs of factor.
	2. A dp array that stores the number of trees possible for an arr element.

Algorithm
1.  Create the Hashmap with the number as key and list of the pair of factos as the value. {a,b} and {b,a} are allowed as long as a!=b.
2.  For every element in arr- iterate over the possible pair of divisors(left and right child in the tree)
3.  if no such pair of divisors- trees[arr[i]] =1;
4.  otherwise for every pair - **trees[root] = trees[root]%MOD + trees[pair.first]%MOD * trees[pair.second]%MOD**. we know for sure that pair.first and pair.second have already been populated since we're moving in ascending order.
5.  return ans%MOD.

Time complexity = (O(nlogn +n^2 + n^2)) = O(n2)
Space complexity = O(n + n) = O(n)

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/df9338c4-41cb-4cf4-bf16-b938392ac2df_1660031312.1613998.png)


The code is as follows-

```
class Solution {
public:
    // Global variables to help with MOD
    int MOD= pow(10,9)+7;

    //factor hashmap is gonna contain the pair of factors for that key
    unordered_map<int,vector<pair<int,int>>> factor;
    // DP hashmap, will contain the no of trees possible for the key
    unordered_map<int,long long> trees;

    int numFactoredBinaryTrees(vector<int>& arr) {

        int n=arr.size();
        // create a set of original array for O(1) checking of the second factor
        unordered_set<int> s(arr.begin(),arr.end());
        // sorting in O(nlogn), can be done without this, but since overall complexity is O(n*n) due to divisor loop, this will not affect it.
        sort(arr.begin(),arr.end());

        // create the Divisor hashmap,
        for (int i=n-1;i>=0;i--){
            // set the possible trees to 1 for every tree, this represents the tree without any child
            trees[arr[i]]=1;
            // considering arr[i] to be the root
            int root = arr[i];
            for(int j=i-1;j>=0;j--){
                // A break statement can be added here to break if arr[j]<sqrt(n),in my case i dont do it, since it leads to factors like (case i) (a,b ) and (b,a ) to be populated if a!=b otherwise (case ii) (a,a) is only populated once, this is in line as case i are two different possibilities of subtree, while case ii is only 1 subtree
                if(root%arr[j]==0){
                    if(s.find(root/arr[j])!=s.end()){
                        if(factor.find(root)!=factor.end()){
                            factor[root].push_back(make_pair(arr[j],root/arr[j]));
                        }
                        else{
                            factor[root]={make_pair(arr[j],root/arr[j])};
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
            // at the end of this j loop, arr[i] has its factor in the hash table
        }


        // now the preparation is done for the meat of the solution
        int ans =0;
        for (int i=0;i<n;i++){
            // consider arr[i] to be root
            int root= arr[i];
            // if root does not have any factors, this code just adds 1 to the answer
            if(factor.find(root)==factor.end()){
                ans+=trees[root];
                continue;
            }
            // else if  we have factors, get the factors from the hasmap.
            vector<pair<int,int>> divisors = factor[root];
            // for every pair of divisor(notice here we are going in increasing order, This is necessary for DP to work as the number of trees for factors will already be populated for the larger number)
            for( int j=0;j<divisors.size();j++){
                pair<int,int> p = divisors[j];

                // add (no of possible trees for left subtree(divisor1) multiplied by no of possible trees for right subtree(divisor2) ) + MOD is distributive over multipplciation
                trees[root]= trees[root]%MOD + (trees[p.first]%MOD)*(trees[p.second]%MOD);
            }

            // at end of j loop we have the no of trees possible for arr[i] so add to answer
            ans=ans%MOD + trees[root]%MOD;

        }
        // return the answer
        return ans%MOD;

    }
};
```

