**Intution** : *sort the array and use **HashMap** to record each Integer, and the number of trees that can be formed with that Integer as root* 

*  we are initializing **dp** with **1** because each integer will always have one tree with only itself.
* Let's suppose we want 18 as root and we have the nodes with value 3 and 6 So, `dp[18] = dp[18] + no ways of trees that can be obtained with 6 as root * 3 as root ` (here for better understanding we are taking dp[18] but actaully it is `dp[pos of 18]` )
* finally we sum all the number of trees that can be formed with that integer ie `for(auto x : dp)  res+=x ;`
```
class Solution {
public:
    const int mod = 1e9+7;
    int numFactoredBinaryTrees(vector<int>& arr) {
        long long res=0,n=arr.size();
        vector<long long> dp(n,1);
        unordered_map<long long,long long> mp;

        sort(arr.begin(),arr.end());
        for(long long i=0;i<n;i++) mp[arr[i]]=i;


        for(long long i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(long long j=i-1; j>=0; j--)
            {
                if(arr[i]%arr[j]==0)
                {
                    long long div = arr[i]/arr[j];
                    if(mp.count(div)) dp[i]+=(dp[j]*dp[mp[div]])%mod;
                }
            }
        }

        for(auto x : dp)  res+=x ;
        return res%mod;
    }
};
```

