**Thinking Process:**
First look at this question, makes me think of [Leetcode 53. Maximum Subarray](https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-subarray/).
```
int maxSubArray(vector<int>& nums) {
	int cur = nums[0], result = cur;
	for (int i = 1; i < nums.size(); i++) {
		cur = max(nums[i], cur + nums[i]);
		result = max(result, cur);
	}
	return result;
}
```

A naive way is to loop input array k times and use the same idea mentioned above. And of course it's a TLE.

```
int kConcatenationMaxSum(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
	int result = 0, cur_max = 0;
	int M = 1e9 + 7;
	for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
		for (int n : arr) {
			cur_max = max(cur_max + n, n) % M;
			result = max(result, cur_max) % M;
		}
	}
	return result;
}
```

But now I have the result for k == 1 at least, now let's think about k == 2. We can easily find that there are 3 cases for k == 2:

1. max subarray is somewhere in the middle and the second repeat does not help at all. ex. arr = [-1,  1,  -1], repeat twice, arr2 = [-1, 1, -1, -1, 1, -1], max subarray is still 1;
2. max subarray is somewhere in the middle and the second repeat can offer some help. ex. arr = [-1, 4, -1], repeat twice, arr2 = [-1, 4, -1, -1, 4 ,-1], max subarray increases from 4 to [4, -1, -1, 4] -> 6. Further, we can easily find that the extra offer is the sum of the arr = [-1, 4, -1] -> 2; **sum > 0 is the key difference from case 1**. And we can easily extend this case to any k > 2 as well, result = result + (k - 1) * sum; 
3. max subarray is at the end of the array and the head of second repeat can offer some help. ex. arr = [1, -4, 1], repeat twice, arr2 = [1, -4, 1, 1, -4, 1], max subarray increases from 1 to 2; This is a special case which will not be affected by more repeated arrays. 

As we think through k == 2, we already have the idea to extend to any k!

**Code:**
```
int kConcatenationMaxSum(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
	long result = 0, cur_max = 0, sum = 0;
	int M = 1e9 + 7;
	// basic solution from Leetcode 53
	for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) {
		cur_max = max(cur_max + arr[i], (long)arr[i]);
		result = max(result, cur_max);
		sum += arr[i];
	}
	// k < 2, return result from basic solution
	if (k < 2) return result % M;
	// sum > 0, case 2
	if (sum > 0) return (result + (k - 1) * sum) % M;
	// another round to catch case 3
	for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) {
		cur_max = max(cur_max + arr[i], (long)arr[i]);
		result = max(result, cur_max);
	}
	return result % M;
}
```

