The problem is similar to [875. Koko Eating Bananas](https://leetcode.com/problems/koko-eating-bananas/discuss/152506/Binary-Search-Java-Python-with-Explanations/). Given a linear searching space [lo, hi], [mi, hi] (lo <= mi) satisfy a property, we can use Binary Searc to get mi.

Here, we play with the searching space of `remaining`:
```
inventory = [1, 2, 3] as below
        x
      x x
    x x x
i = 0 1 2

Let's define remaining = 2 as below:
      x x
    x x x
i = 0 1 2

      x  
    x x x
i = 0 1 2

        x  
    x x x
i = 0 1 2

they can cover orders = 1 an orders = 2.

Our problem becomes with the given `orders`, what is `remaining`?

With `remaining` decreasing, `orders` gets larger.
```

Here, searching space for `remaining` is monotone regarding whether they can satisfy `orders`. 

If searching space of `remaining` is `[lo, hi]`, the subrange `[lo, K]` can make orders >= `orders`, our aim is to find such `K` in order to get maximum profit.

```
class Solution {
    private static final int MOD = 1000000007;

    public int maxProfit(int[] inventory, int orders) {
        int maxFreq = 0;
        for (int freq : inventory) {
            maxFreq = Math.max(freq, maxFreq);
        }

        long lo = 0, hi = maxFreq; // Search space of remaining balls of each inventory[i]
        while (lo <= hi) {
            long mi = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;
            long cntOrders = countOrders(mi, inventory);
            if (cntOrders == orders) {
                lo = mi;
                break;
            } else if (cntOrders < orders) {
                hi = mi - 1;
            } else {
                lo = mi + 1;
            }
        }

        return getProfitFromOrders(lo, orders, inventory);
    }

    private int getProfitFromOrders(long remaining, int orders, int[] inventory) {
        long ordersSoFar = 0, profit = 0;
        for (int freq : inventory) {
            if (freq <= remaining)
                continue;
            profit = (profit + (freq + remaining + 1) * (freq - remaining) / 2 % MOD) % MOD;
            ordersSoFar += freq - remaining;
        }
        profit = (profit + (orders - ordersSoFar) * remaining % MOD) % MOD;

        return (int)profit;
    }

    // For each inventory[i], we sell (inventory[i] - target) orders, count the total orders
    private long countOrders(long remaining, int[] inventory) {
        long sum = 0;
        for (int freq : inventory) {
            if (freq < remaining)
                continue;
            sum += freq - remaining;
        }
        return sum;
    }
}
```

