**greedy/sorting**
**time: `O(N)`; space: `O(1)`**

It's preferable to start from the most abundant balls.

This is the basic idea:
* sort data to get a Young diagram;
* slice diagram horizontally and 'add up' the horizontal bars one by one until the number of added element reaches the `orders` limit.
* the last bar may need some extra consideration as only part of it will be added.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8f0461de-b524-4e45-bc8f-46d6f0c566a9_1654015597.187999.png)

Here's a more detailed picture:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/c594f439-579c-42a5-b8f9-d09753e51d2e_1654013894.6066058.png)


**Useful identity:**

`(s+1) + (s+2) + ... + t = t*(t+1)/2 - s*(s+1)/2`

that is based on:

`1 + 2 + 3 +  ... + t = t*(t+1)/2`.

```
int maxProfit(vector<int>& n, int o) 
{
	sort(begin(n), end(n), greater{});
	int out{}, i{}, t{n[0]};
	for(int t1{t}; i*(t-t1)<o; )
    {
        out  = (out+i*(t*(t+1ll)-t1*(t1+1ll))/2)%1000000007;
        o   -= i*(t-t1);
        t    = exchange(t1, i<size(n)? n[i] : 0);
        i    = distance(begin(n), upper_bound(begin(n)+i, end(n), t, greater{}));
    }
    long long t2 = t-o/i;
    return (out+i*(t*(t+1ll)-t2*(t2+1ll))/2+o%i*t2)%1000000007;
}
```

